ve controlled the collection and communication of information, Bennett also deepens our understanding of policymaking theory. Regulating Privacy will be welcomed by political sciences—especially those working in comparative public policy, American politics, organization theory, and technology and politics—political economists, information systems analysts, and others concerned with issues of privacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aData protectionxLaw and legislationzEurope. 0aData protectionxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aPrivacy, Right ofzEurope. 0aPrivacy, Right ofzUnited States. 4aHistory Of Technology. 4aLegal History & Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172213440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501722134423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501722134/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles